Comment: The Barcza opening is a very flexible one allowing many defensive setups for black.  Some possibilities include; the Kings Indian Attack, the Sicilian, the Catalan, and the Reti.  The point, with this move white proudly states, "I know stuff."  Yes, but how much stuff does he know?  : )
: ) These two move (Bishop and Queen) make me smile every time.  I can remember learning Fisher's mate a long time ago in a far off place...

If 17... Kh8 then 18. Qh5, h6  19. Ne8!, f6  20. Rxf6!, Rxf6 (20... Rxe8 21. Rxh6+, Kg8  22. Qxe8# or 20... gxf6  21. Qxh6+, Kg8  22. Qg7#) 21. Bxf6, Kg8 (21... gxf6 22. Qxh6, Kg8  23. Qg7#) 22. Qg6, Kf8  23. Qxg7+, Kxe8  24. Qe7#.  17... gxf6 causes a need for white to find a star move later.

18... Nd5 was the only try, though, still losing.  After which 19. Qh5, c3 (and now the star move) 20. Bxc3!!, Nxc3  21. Rh6 and any move made by black doesn't stop checkmate.  For instance 21... Kg7  22. Rxh7+, Kf6  23. Re1, Be6 (black can prolong the game with a knight imposition, but only by one move since the rook will snap it off)  24.
